"CORE_NARRATIVE: Real-world scenes consist of **mixed reflectances**, yet existing models either fail to generalize across material types or suffer from prohibitive computational costs. By introducing a **physics-inspired dual-mask** multi-directional EPI architecture and rigorously defining the **physical limits of angular frequency analysis**, we break the reflectance barrier to deliver a **lightweight unified baseline** for edge deployment.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open by contrasting the idealized assumption of uniform surfaces with the messy reality of **mixed-reflectance environments**, immediately highlighting the edge-deployment bottleneck caused by **computationally heavy unified models**.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Transition by exposing that existing methods treat reflectance variations as a purely data-driven problem requiring massive parameters, ignoring the underlying **physical light transport properties** and the **hardware sampling limits** of angular frequencies.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Justify the **dual-mask modeling mechanism** and **multi-directional EPI** design as a direct physical response to decouple reflectance properties without parameter bloat, while explicitly grounding the frequency branch in our theoretical proof regarding the **Nyquist limits of 9×9 angular sampling**.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Validate the motivation by demonstrating that the **754K-parameter model** achieves superior MAE across Lambertian, Non-Lambertian, and **Mixed domains**, while presenting the statistical **\"negative results\"** that definitively rule out 9×9 frequency-based material classification.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Echo the motivation by reiterating that practical deployment requires both algorithmic efficiency and theoretical clarity, positioning our **lightweight unified architecture** and **hardware sampling guidelines** as the new foundational baseline for **real-world mixed-reflectance applications**."